Argmnents contra: Aristotle's view. — The difficulties which surround such a system are of course great and manifold. Aristotle seems against it; for instance, when he says that the Continuous is infinitely divisible. But, a) Aristode speaks of that which is continuous to our senses; and that, so far as our senses can tell, is indeed made up of innumerable parts. But though infinite for us, they are not so to God. And, h) Ari- stotle distinctly says that the point is the cause of the line; if so, it must be its element, and this dictum is quite in Wyclif's favour (35). The doctrine of indivisible points transcends both our senses and our imagination.
